export interface SectionHtml { anchor: string; html: string }

export const sections: SectionHtml[] = [
 { "anchor": "opener", "html": "<p>Permanent magnets are where I send skeptics who doubt that meV-scale energy differences decide billion-dollar supply chains. The world's traction-magnet material, sintered Nd<span class=\"math\">$_2$</span>Fe<span class=\"math\">$_{14}$</span>B, earns its position from numbers at the edge of what simulation can compute: magnetocrystalline anisotropy energy (MAE) <span class=\"math\">$K_1 \\approx 5$</span>–<span class=\"math\">$6$</span> MJ/m<span class=\"math\">$^3$</span>, polarization <span class=\"math\">$J_s \\approx 1.6$</span> T, Curie temperature <span class=\"math\">$T_c = 585$</span>–<span class=\"math\">$586$</span> K.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"241\">[241]</sup> The anisotropy itself is near-degenerate bookkeeping — 4<span class=\"math\">$f$</span> orbital angular momentum surviving under a weak crystal field — and the 135 K spin-reorientation tilt of the Nd compound is a sub-meV balance that flips sign between isostructural rare earths.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"84\">[84]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"241\">[241]</sup> A method that misranks meV differences misranks magnets; a supply chain built on the misranked magnet inherits the error.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s9-1-1", "html": "<p>As of 2026-07-17 the supply side of this class runs on two clocks. China's April 4, 2025 controls (Announcement No. 18) license seven medium/heavy rare earths — Sm, Gd, Tb, Dy, Lu, Sc, Y, the dopants that keep NdFeB coercive at motor temperatures — and remain fully in force; they were never suspended.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"69\">[69]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"242\">[242]</sup> The October 2025 package, including Announcement 61's extraterritorial 0.1% rule modeled explicitly on the US foreign-direct-product rule, is only <em>suspended</em>, and only until November 10, 2026; the legal consensus reads the measures as a pause, not a repeal — &quot;legally intact and can reactivate without new legislation.&quot;<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"68\">[68]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"243\">[243]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"242\">[242]</sup> Prices have already transmitted the asymmetry: as of June 2026, price trackers report ex-China yttrium oxide near $1{,}100/kg (a <span class=\"math\">$\\times 140$</span> move), dysprosium oxide near $1{,}450/kg (<span class=\"math\">$\\times 4$</span>–<span class=\"math\">$5$</span>), terbium oxide near $4{,}500/kg.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"40\">[40]</sup> The IEA's loss accounting: a 10% disruption in rare-earth-magnet exports corresponds to the production of 6.2 million conventional cars; full reimplementation of controls puts up to $6.5 trillion of annual ex-China output at risk.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"244\">[244]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"242\">[242]</sup> Demand gives the exposure physical form: 1–3 kg of NdFeB per EV traction motor, 1{,}000–2{,}000 kg per wind turbine.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"245\">[245]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"246\">[246]</sup></p>\n<p>I read this evidence as one fact stated twice: the class's value and its simulation error are the same thing. Every substitution pathway priced by governments runs through quantities — <span class=\"math\">$T_c$</span>, anisotropy, coercivity — that ab initio and ML methods handle worst.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s9-2", "html": "<p>Chapter 3's taxonomy assigned magnets to mode 3 (magnetism), with scoreboard Row 9 (missing electronic degrees of freedom) binding and Row 10's 4<span class=\"math\">$f$</span> problem compounding. The structural point of Table 9.1: each quantity a magnet is sold on is pinned by a different failing method at a different length scale, so no single fix rescues the screening funnel.</p>\n<p><strong>Table 9.1 — Error modes blocking REE-free magnet discovery (verified as of 2026-07-17). Unmarked MAE = mean absolute error; magnetocrystalline anisotropy energy is spelled out.</strong></p>\n<div class=\"tablewrap\"><table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>Observable</th>\n<th>Method that fails</th>\n<th>Quantified error</th>\n<th>Discovery consequence</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"math\">$T_c$</span>, screening</td>\n<td>DFT→Heisenberg mapping, mean-field decoupling</td>\n<td>15–35% band, non-systematic sign: Fe<span class=\"math\">$_2$</span>B 1{,}570 vs 1{,}013 K (+35%); Co<span class=\"math\">$_2$</span>B 290 vs 429 K (<span class=\"math\">$\\times 1.5$</span> underestimate) <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"13\">[13]</sup>; ~30% worst-case exchange overestimate in LSMO <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"80\">[80]</sup></td>\n<td>Sign-unstable go/no-go on the 400–500 K operating window</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"math\">$T_c$</span>, high-throughput</td>\n<td>Automated DFT predictor (32 magnets)</td>\n<td>MAE <span class=\"math\">$\\approx 126$</span> K <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"247\">[247]</sup></td>\n<td>Ranks candidates; cannot certify them</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"math\">$T_c$</span>, ML regressors</td>\n<td>LLM-mined and composition-only models</td>\n<td>MAE 38.8–62 K; systematic underestimation above 500 K <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"248\">[248]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"249\">[249]</sup></td>\n<td>Extrapolation-blind in the traction-magnet regime</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Coercivity <span class=\"math\">$H_c$</span></td>\n<td>Continuum micromagnetics</td>\n<td>~5<span class=\"math\">$\\times$</span> overestimate without grain-boundary engineering (Brown's paradox) <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"14\">[14]</sup></td>\n<td>Intrinsic screening cannot see the property that sells</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Anisotropy <span class=\"math\">$K_1$</span> (4<span class=\"math\">$f$</span>)</td>\n<td>Semilocal DFT</td>\n<td>Self-interaction error &quot;contradicts Hund's rules&quot;; single-ion theory &gt;20% error with <span class=\"math\">$J$</span>-mixing <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"84\">[84]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"250\">[250]</sup></td>\n<td>Anisotropy ranking unreliable across rare-earth series</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Phase stability (Fe–Ni)</td>\n<td>Foundation MACE MLIPs</td>\n<td>bcc→hcp transition-pressure trend &quot;contrary to experiment&quot; <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"251\">[251]</sup></td>\n<td>Qualitative failure in the tetrataenite alloy family</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<p>Read top to bottom, Table 9.1 spans four failure regimes: electronic exchange (meV), relativistic spin–orbit (meV/atom), continuum defect physics (10 nm–10 μm), and learned training distributions. The <span class=\"math\">$T_c$</span> band is the most corrosive row because the error's <em>sign</em> is unstable — the same decoupling scheme that overshoots Fe<span class=\"math\">$_2$</span>B by 35% undershoots Co<span class=\"math\">$_2$</span>B by a factor of 1.5 — so no constant correction exists. The coercivity row is the commercially decisive one: a funnel can rank <span class=\"math\">$M_s$</span>, <span class=\"math\">$K_1$</span>, and <span class=\"math\">$T_c$</span> perfectly and still say nothing about the figure of merit a motor designer buys. The MLIP row is the most strategically corrosive: a foundation model that reverses the bcc–hcp trend in the Fe–Ni family forecloses the cheap rescue of &quot;just retrain on the right alloy system&quot; — the failure is in the training distribution, not the architecture, and escaping it means rebuilding data, which is precisely the work this report argues is under-priced.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s9-2-1", "html": "<p>Mean-field decoupling of the Heisenberg mapping neglects short-range order, and the 15–35% band is documented end to end: the Fe<span class=\"math\">$_2$</span>B/Co<span class=\"math\">$_2$</span>B sign instability, a ~30% worst-case exchange overestimate in careful LSMO work, and persistent overestimation even in DFT+DMFT for CrO<span class=\"math\">$_2$</span>.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"13\">[13]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"80\">[80]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"252\">[252]</sup> Automated high-throughput predictors reach MAE <span class=\"math\">$\\approx 126$</span> K across 32 magnets — usable for ranking, not certification.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"247\">[247]</sup> ML regressors look better on paper (MAE 38.8–62 K) but systematically <em>underestimate</em> <span class=\"math\">$T_c$</span> above 500 K, where training data thins — extrapolation blindness exactly where traction magnets live.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"248\">[248]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"249\">[249]</sup></p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s9-2-2", "html": "<p>Coercivity is extrinsic — set by defect nucleation and grain-boundary chemistry, not intrinsic anisotropy. Continuum micromagnetics overestimates <span class=\"math\">$H_c$</span> by about a factor of five without grain-boundary engineering (Brown's paradox), and realized coercivity empirically runs at 15–30% of the anisotropy field; SmFe<span class=\"math\">$_{12}$</span> model films reach only 15%.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"14\">[14]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"253\">[253]</sup> Ce-substituted NdFeB makes the dependence vivid: an <em>abnormal coercivity peak at 20–30% Ce</em> arises from CeFe<span class=\"math\">$_2$</span> grain-boundary decoupling — invisible to unit-cell DFT, and unflagged by any composition-only screening model.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"254\">[254]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"255\">[255]</sup></p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s9-2-3", "html": "<p>Rare-earth 4<span class=\"math\">$f$</span> states break standard exchange-correlation functionals: self-interaction error &quot;contradicts Hund's rules and plagues magnetocrystalline anisotropy calculations.&quot;<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"84\">[84]</sup> The workarounds are bespoke — open-core treatments, self-interaction corrections, full potentials — and single-ion anisotropy theory &quot;falls beyond a 20% accuracy limit for most permanent magnet materials&quot; once <span class=\"math\">$J$</span>-mixing is included.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"256\">[256]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"250\">[250]</sup> Sign changes of the anisotropy across isostructural rare-earth series defeat transferability.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"84\">[84]</sup></p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s9-2-4", "html": "<p>A 2026 benchmark (&quot;Can MACE Potentials Accurately Describe Magnetism and Phase Stability in Fe–Ni Alloys?&quot;) finds all tested foundation MACE models predict the bcc→hcp transition pressure <em>increasing</em> with Ni content — &quot;contrary to experiment,&quot; traced to missing high-pressure magnetic-collapse physics.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"251\">[251]</sup> Fe–Ni is the tetrataenite system: today's best universal potentials get its phase stability qualitatively wrong. Magnetism-aware MLIPs exist — magnetic Moment Tensor Potentials fit to <em>magnetic</em> forces relax bcc Fe–Al reliably — but are system-specific; no universal MLIP carries spin as a first-class variable.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"257\">[257]</sup></p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s9-3", "html": "<p>Two demonstrated fixes define the lever. First, hybrid finite-temperature theory: Patrick &amp; Staunton's parameter-free scheme — disordered-local-moment (DLM) itinerant 3<span class=\"math\">$d$</span> plus crystal-field 4<span class=\"math\">$f$</span> — reproduces SmCo<span class=\"math\">$_5$</span> <span class=\"math\">$K_1 = 21.3$</span> MJ/m<span class=\"math\">$^3$</span> at 300 K and the NdCo<span class=\"math\">$_5$</span> spin reorientations, but only by abandoning plain DFT total-energy differences; a 2023 PRB adds that the Fe sublattice's own anisotropy is indispensable in Nd<span class=\"math\">$_2$</span>Fe<span class=\"math\">$_{14}$</span>B, an effect 4<span class=\"math\">$f$</span>-only models miss.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"258\">[258]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"259\">[259]</sup> Second, spin-aware MLIPs: SpinGNN++ reaches sub-meV accuracy on spin-lattice Hamiltonians — the bar for magnets, ~20<span class=\"math\">$\\times$</span> tighter than the ~20 meV/atom at which universal models plateau — and UMA-class foundation heads now accept spin and charge as explicit inputs.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"100\">[100]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"101\">[101]</sup> The data-cost lever is multi-fidelity training: one study finds 90% GGA + 10% SCAN labels matching a model trained on 8<span class=\"math\">$\\times$</span> as much SCAN; the recipe transfers to spin-polarized reference sets.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"20\">[20]</sup></p>\n<p>My working bet: the winning stack here is not a universal magnetic MLIP but a fidelity stack — spin-aware potentials trained against DLM + crystal-field references, micromagnetics coupled to <em>measured</em> grain-boundary chemistry rather than idealized boundaries. Coercivity, not <span class=\"math\">$T_c$</span>, is where simulation adds what screening cannot.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s9-4", "html": "<p>The honest position is that substitution has underdelivered for four decades; Table 9.2 shows why, candidate by candidate.</p>\n<p><strong>Table 9.2 — REE-free and reduced-REE substitute scorecard vs Nd<span class=\"math\">$_2$</span>Fe<span class=\"math\">$_{14}$</span>B (<span class=\"math\">$J_s \\approx 1.6$</span> T, <span class=\"math\">$K_1 \\approx 5$</span>–<span class=\"math\">$6$</span> MJ/m<span class=\"math\">$^3$</span>, <span class=\"math\">$T_c = 585$</span>–<span class=\"math\">$586$</span> K <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"241\">[241]</sup>). Status as of 2026-07-17.</strong></p>\n<div class=\"tablewrap\"><table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>Candidate</th>\n<th>Intrinsic metrics vs NdFeB (<span class=\"math\">$M_s$</span>/<span class=\"math\">$K_1$</span>/<span class=\"math\">$T_c$</span>)</th>\n<th>Gap type</th>\n<th>Nearest commercial milestone (date)</th>\n<th>Source</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>MnBi</td>\n<td><span class=\"math\">$K_1 \\approx 1.6$</span> MJ/m<span class=\"math\">$^3$</span>; <span class=\"math\">$M_s$</span> 75–81 emu/g; theoretical (BH)<span class=\"math\">$_\\text{max}$</span> ~20 MGOe ≈ half of NdFeB <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"260\">[260]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"261\">[261]</sup></td>\n<td>Densification: ~70% of powder <span class=\"math\">$H_{cj}$</span> lost on consolidation; ±5 °C processing window <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"260\">[260]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"262\">[262]</sup></td>\n<td>Ames R&amp;D 100 grain-isolation coating (2025); Magnet Energy melt-spin route <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"263\">[263]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"260\">[260]</sup></td>\n<td><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"260\">[260]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"261\">[261]</sup></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>τ-MnAlC</td>\n<td><span class=\"math\">$T_c = 653$</span> K; (BH)<span class=\"math\">$_\\text{max} \\approx 14$</span> MGOe (<span class=\"math\">$\\approx$</span>110 kJ/m<span class=\"math\">$^3$</span>; the source prints an irreconcilable &quot;12 kJ/m<span class=\"math\">$^3$</span> (14 MGOe)&quot; pairing — the MGOe figure is the credible one); carbon lowers <span class=\"math\">$T_c$</span> and anisotropy field <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"14\">[14]</sup></td>\n<td>Metastable τ window (51–58% Mn); hot-extrusion cost <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"14\">[14]</sup></td>\n<td>ML + ab initio + micromagnetic rescue pipelines (2024–) <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"14\">[14]</sup></td>\n<td><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"14\">[14]</sup></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Fe<span class=\"math\">$_{16}$</span>N<span class=\"math\">$_2$</span> (Niron)</td>\n<td>Claimed 2.4 T vs 1.4 T for RE magnets; independent ceiling 2.6 <span class=\"math\">$\\mu_B$</span>/Fe; decomposes ~175 °C <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"264\">[264]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"265\">[265]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"253\">[253]</sup></td>\n<td>40-year reproducibility controversy; phase purity; thermal stability <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"265\">[265]</sup></td>\n<td>Sartell Plant 1: 1,500 t/yr, operations early 2027; Minneapolis pilot &gt;5 t/yr running <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"72\">[72]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"266\">[266]</sup></td>\n<td><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"265\">[265]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"72\">[72]</sup></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>L1<span class=\"math\">$_0$</span> FeNi tetrataenite</td>\n<td>Predicted (BH)<span class=\"math\">$_\\text{max}$</span> mid-tier: below RE super-magnets, above Alnico/ferrites <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"267\">[267]</sup></td>\n<td>Ordering kinetics (Box 9.1); bulk (BH)<span class=\"math\">$_\\text{max}$</span> unverified <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"267\">[267]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"268\">[268]</sup></td>\n<td>P-assisted bulk casting &quot;within seconds&quot; (Cambridge, 2022); patent filed; no volume producer <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"268\">[268]</sup></td>\n<td><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"267\">[267]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"268\">[268]</sup></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>SmFe<span class=\"math\">$_{12}$</span> (film)</td>\n<td><span class=\"math\">$\\mu_0 M_s = 1.78$</span> T, <span class=\"math\">$\\mu_0 H_a = 8.2$</span> T, <span class=\"math\">$K_1 = 4.37$</span> MJ/m<span class=\"math\">$^3$</span>, <span class=\"math\">$T_c = 859$</span> K — all superior to NdFeB <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"253\">[253]</sup></td>\n<td>No non-magnetic grain-boundary phase; film <span class=\"math\">$H_c$</span> only 15% of <span class=\"math\">$H_a$</span> <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"253\">[253]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"269\">[269]</sup></td>\n<td>Best bulk <span class=\"math\">$H_c$</span> 1.08 T (mechanochemical); Magnet Energy targets &gt;30 MGOe <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"269\">[269]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"270\">[270]</sup></td>\n<td><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"253\">[253]</sup></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Ce-substituted NdFeB</td>\n<td>Ce<span class=\"math\">$_2$</span>Fe<span class=\"math\">$_{14}$</span>B: <span class=\"math\">$T_c = 422$</span> K vs 585 K; Ce<span class=\"math\">$^{4+}$</span> magnetically near-silent <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"254\">[254]</sup></td>\n<td>Intrinsic dilution; squareness degrades &gt;12% Ce <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"271\">[271]</sup></td>\n<td>Commercial in China ~50,000 t/yr at ≤8% Ce; MMP magnets 45 MGOe at 20% Ce <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"271\">[271]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"254\">[254]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"255\">[255]</sup></td>\n<td><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"254\">[254]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"271\">[271]</sup></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>La-Co ferrites</td>\n<td><span class=\"math\">$B_r \\approx 460$</span>–<span class=\"math\">$475$</span> mT; (BH)<span class=\"math\">$_\\text{max} \\approx 41$</span>–<span class=\"math\">$44$</span> kJ/m<span class=\"math\">$^3$</span>; <span class=\"math\">$H_{cj}$</span> 380–430 kA/m <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"272\">[272]</sup></td>\n<td>~8–10<span class=\"math\">$\\times$</span> below sintered NdFeB (35–55 MGOe); 40–50% more motor volume <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"273\">[273]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"274\">[274]</sup></td>\n<td>TDK FB12 commercial since 2007 <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"272\">[272]</sup></td>\n<td><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"272\">[272]</sup></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<p>The scorecard's pattern: five of seven rows fail on processing or microstructure, not intrinsic physics — MnBi's densification, MnAlC's metastability, Fe<span class=\"math\">$_{16}$</span>N<span class=\"math\">$_2$</span>'s phase purity, tetrataenite's kinetics, SmFe<span class=\"math\">$_{12}$</span>'s grain boundaries. The two intrinsic exceptions, Ce dilution and ferrite flux, are thermodynamically priced in and compete only in low/mid grades. This is why screening yields stay brutal: a Materials-Project binary funnel passes 18 candidates from ~20,000 entries (~0.1%), Fe–N screening flags 15 more with anisotropy above 1 MJ/m<span class=\"math\">$^3$</span>, and survivors then die at the decisive step because DFT rankings are &quot;poorly transferable across structural classes.&quot;<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"275\">[275]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"276\">[276]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"277\">[277]</sup> As of 2026-07-17, no REE-free magnet meets NdFeB traction specifications in volume production.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"277\">[277]</sup> Niron's 1,500 t/yr from 2027 is ~1% of China's ~240 kt/yr magnet output — a resilience hedge, not displacement — and ferrites need 40–50% more motor volume (US DOE) and, per secondary industry figures, 8–12 kg of magnet where NdFeB needs ~1.2 kg.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"72\">[72]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"278\">[278]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"274\">[274]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"279\">[279]</sup></p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s9-5", "html": "<p>Washington has answered the chokepoint with a dated instrument stack: the USGS final 2025 list expanded 50 → 60 minerals in November 2025 with all magnet rare earths retained; DOE's CMEI office issued the $134M REE Demonstration Facility NOFO (December 2025) and selected Phoenix Tailings ($66M, waste-derived metals) and a Colorado School of Mines-led team (red-mud-to-REE) for the balance of the $134M award in June 2026; the DoD–MP Materials deal (July 2025) took $400M of convertible equity and set a ten-year $110/kg NdPr price floor, with the &quot;10X&quot; magnet plant commissioning 2028; ARPA-E's MAGNITO program — a $20M NOFO within a ~$72M program-level effort, the larger figure single-sourced to one awardee announcement — funds AI/ML plus high-throughput experimentation for novel magnet chemistries and microstructures; and the DOE ban on Chinese-origin rare-earth magnets in defense applications takes effect January 1, 2027.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"39\">[39]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"280\">[280]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"281\">[281]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"58\">[58]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"57\">[57]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"282\">[282]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"283\">[283]</sup></p>\n<p>Beijing's architecture pairs control with capability: rare-earth functional materials sit in the 15FYP's upgrade tier (提质升级); annual quotas (2024: 270,000 t mining, 254,000 t separation) regulate volume; and the midstream reality — roughly 60–70% of mining, 85–90%+ of separation, 90–94% of magnet production — means even a perfect substitute discovered elsewhere must clear conversion infrastructure China owns.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"32\">[32]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"284\">[284]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"278\">[278]</sup> Ce-bearing magnets are already commercial inside China at ~50,000 t/yr in low/mid grades.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"271\">[271]</sup> I read the two programs as mirror images: Washington buys down midstream risk with price floors and equity while Beijing defends the midstream and upgrades its materials tier. Neither side has funded the coercivity-from-microstructure problem of §9.2.2 as a first-class program — MAGNITO's chemistry-and-microstructure mandate comes closest.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s9-6", "html": "<p>This chapter feeds flagship discovery chain 2: multi-fidelity and spin-aware MLIPs → NdFeB-class REE-free magnets → motors and turbines immune to export controls. Box 9.1 is my emblem of what a discovery in this class looks like — and why it did not come from a screening funnel.</p>\n<p><strong>Box 9.1 — Tetrataenite: the thermodynamics was known; the kinetics took geological time.</strong></p>\n<p>L1<span class=\"math\">$_0$</span>-ordered FeNi has been computationally respectable for decades; its formation is restricted by &quot;a low atomic ordering temperature and consequently sluggish kinetics,&quot; so observed bulk samples came from meteorites cooled over millions of years, or from lattices agitated by neutron bombardment or severe plastic deformation.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"267\">[267]</sup> Equilibrium screening — formation energies, <span class=\"math\">$M_s$</span>, <span class=\"math\">$K_1$</span> — would have ranked tetrataenite a plausible mid-tier magnet and stopped there; the blocker was kinetic and therefore invisible to every equilibrium method. The unlock came in 2022, when a Cambridge team noticed that meteorites carry phosphorus, showed that phosphorus accelerates Fe/Ni diffusion, and cast hard-magnetic tetrataenite in bulk &quot;within seconds, without having to wait millions of years&quot;; Cambridge Enterprise and the Austrian Academy of Sciences filed the patent, and as of 2026-07 there is still no volume producer.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"268\">[268]</sup> Two lessons for chain 2. First, the decisive variable was a diffusion accelerator — process chemistry, not a better exchange-correlation functional; today's foundation MLIPs, which misorder even Fe–Ni's qualitative phase-stability trend, would not have proposed it.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"251\">[251]</sup> Second, kinetics is itself a discoverable variable: nitrogen-insertion/topotactic-extraction routes reach the same L1<span class=\"math\">$_0$</span> phase by a deliberately non-equilibrium path.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"285\">[285]</sup> &quot;Exists&quot; (2022) to &quot;ships&quot; (no one, as of 2026-07-17) measures how far a seconds-fast breakthrough sits from a motor.</p>\n<p>Where does this leave an independent lab? My position: coercivity is the underpriced axis of this class. Intrinsic screening is crowded and error-capped; a validated microstructure-to-coercivity model — micromagnetics fed by measured grain-boundary chemistry on one of the seven systems in Table 9.2 — converts simulation from a ranking tool into a design tool at single-lab scale. The external gate is dated: on 2026-11-10 the October 2025 suspension lapses and, absent an extension, the extraterritorial 0.1% rule reactivates automatically; every program in §9.5 is priced off that date.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"68\">[68]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"243\">[243]</sup> Between now and then, the most valuable magnet science is not another screened candidate but a coercivity prediction that survives contact with a sintering furnace — that is what turns Table 9.2's gaps from fatal to priced.</p>\n" },
]
